<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="cb03007f-191a-5cc9-9dac-892497fd8562" activityNameId="955b9cdc-641b-4317-9ae1-0d173882d66c" parentActivityId="7f71c0c4-d917-5ad9-b629-0051fee116ca" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">ground granulated blast furnace slag production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">GGBFS; slag cement</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">From transport of molten iron blast furnace slag for granulation from pig iron production (within the steel plant). Granulation is followed by dewatering and/or drying, crushing, grinding and finally storage.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity ends with the storage of the finished product (GGBFS) in silo. 
This activity does neither include packaging and distribution of the final product, nor the treatment of wastewater generated in the granulation process step.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of ground granulated blast furnace slag (GGBFS) in the global geography. This dataset was built as a weighted average of regional datasets of the same activityName.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The ground granulated blast furnace slag (GGBFS) is a by-product of iron manufacturing which when added to concrete improves its properties such as workability, strength and durability. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">GGBFS is a supplementary cementious material used as a partial replacement for Portland cement in concrete. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">This activity includes the process steps (i) quenching/granulation, (ii) dewatering and/or drying, (iii) crushing, (iv) grinding, and (v) storage in pile and silo. </text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="8561dfe4-c9a0-4582-a7a2-90576f098bca">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">239:Manufacture of non-metallic mineral products n.e.c.</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="7846b897-7c04-4f9f-b607-2b83fcd9a74c">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RoW</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset is a weighted average built from the following geographies: IN, US, ZA.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This material is obtained by the heating of iron ore, limestone and coke at a temperature about 1500 degree Celsius. The process is carried out in a blast furnace.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The formation of GGBFS is not direct. The by-product of iron manufacturing is a molten slag and molten iron. The molten slag consists of alumina and silica, also with the certain amount of oxides.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">This slag is later granulated by cooling it. For this, it is allowed to pass through a high-pressure water get. This result in quenching of the particles which results in granules of size lesser than 5mm in diameter.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">The main constituents of blast furnace slag are CaO, SiO2, Al2O3 and MgO. These are the minerals that are found in most of the cementitious substances.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">The particles are further dried and ground in a rotating ball mill to form a fine powder, known as ground granulated blast furnace slag cement.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2001-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset is considered valid at least from the earliest start date (2001) until the latest end date (2017) of the regional datasets with the same activity name.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
